# app/db/

Database layer: connection management and SQL queries for Postgres.

## Why this exists
Routes should not contain raw SQL and connection boilerplate. Keeping DB code here:
- Reduces duplication
- Improves testability
- Avoids routes becoming unmaintainable
- Makes team collaboration cleaner

## Typical files
- `connection.py`:
  - Responsible for opening/closing DB connections
  - Reads DB config from environment variables or a `.env` file
- `queries.py` (or multiple files later):
  - Contains SQL and query functions (e.g. `get_users()`, `create_post(...)`)
  - Returns plain Python data structures to the routes layer

## What belongs here
- Connection helpers
- Query functions
- SQL statements

## What does NOT belong here
- Flask route decorators or request handling
- Template rendering
- Front-end JavaScript


🗄️ Database Onboarding (Local Development)

This project uses PostgreSQL running locally on your machine.
The database schema is created automatically via a Python script — you do not manually run SQL files.

Follow these steps once per machine.

1️⃣ Install PostgreSQL
Windows

Download PostgreSQL from:
👉 https://www.postgresql.org/download/windows/

Run the installer

During setup:

Remember the postgres password

Leave default port: 5432

Make sure PostgreSQL Server and psql are installed

After install, verify in PowerShell:

psql --version

2️⃣ Create database + role (one-time setup)

Open PowerShell and log in as the Postgres superuser:

psql -U postgres


Enter the password you set during installation.

Create the app role
CREATE USER snipsnap WITH PASSWORD 'snipsnap_pw';

Create the database
CREATE DATABASE snipsnap_db OWNER snipsnap;

Exit psql
\q


💡 You may change usernames/passwords if you want — just keep .env in sync.

3️⃣ Set up Python environment

From the repo root:

python -m venv .venv
.venv\Scripts\activate
pip install -r requirements.txt


If not already installed:

pip install psycopg[binary] python-dotenv

4️⃣ Create .env file (required)
Copy the template
copy .env.example .env

Edit .env

Example:

DATABASE_URL=postgresql://snipsnap:snipsnap_pw@127.0.0.1:5432/snipsnap_db
FLASK_SECRET_KEY=local-dev-secret
FLASK_DEBUG=1


⚠️ Do not commit .env — it contains secrets.

5️⃣ Initialise the database schema

This step:

creates all tables

adds constraints

is safe to re-run

From repo root:

python app/db/init_db.py


Expected output:

Connecting to DB via DATABASE_URL...
Applying schema from: app/db/db.sql
Statements to run: X
✅ Database schema applied successfully.

6️⃣ Start the app
python app/app.py


The app now connects to your local PostgreSQL database.

🔁 Resetting the database (development only)

If you need to wipe all tables and start fresh:

psql -U snipsnap -d snipsnap_db


Then run:

DROP SCHEMA public CASCADE;
CREATE SCHEMA public;
GRANT ALL ON SCHEMA public TO snipsnap;
GRANT ALL ON SCHEMA public TO public;
\q


Recreate tables:

python app/db/init_db.py

❗ Common Issues
Password works in psql but not in Python

Your terminal may have an old DATABASE_URL environment variable set.

Check:

echo $env:DATABASE_URL


Clear it:

Remove-Item Env:DATABASE_URL


Restart the terminal and retry.

DATABASE_URL is not set

Ensure .env exists in the repo root

Ensure python-dotenv is installed

Ensure you are running commands from the repo root

📌 Design Notes (Important)

The app does not create databases or roles automatically

This is intentional (security + portability)

init_db.py only manages schema, not infrastructure

All filtering and selection logic happens in SQL, not frontend JS

✅ You’re Done

Once these steps are complete, you’re fully onboarded and can start:

writing queries in app/db/queries.py

building galleries and pages

extending the schema safely